Title:
Process Injection Part II

Type:
Blog Post

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
- This post continues a series on Windows process injection, focusing on practical implementation details beyond basic CreateRemoteThread-style injection.  
- It explains how to execute code in a remote process by allocating memory, writing a payload, and triggering execution using alternative thread creation/execution primitives.  
- The write-up emphasizes Windows internals involved in remote memory operations and thread context manipulation, highlighting common pitfalls (permissions, architecture mismatch, memory protections).  
- It’s primarily useful for red teamers, pentesters, and malware developers building or analyzing injection tradecraft, and for blue teamers wanting to understand what telemetry these steps generate.  
- It’s interesting because it breaks injection down into discrete API-level stages that map cleanly to detection opportunities (handle opens, RWX transitions, remote thread start).

Technical Focus:
- OpenProcess / process handle access rights
- VirtualAllocEx / VirtualProtectEx remote memory allocation & protection changes
- WriteProcessMemory payload staging
- Remote thread execution primitives (e.g., CreateRemoteThread / NtCreateThreadEx or equivalents)
- Thread context / execution flow control (where applicable)

Use Cases:
- Implementing a basic-to-intermediate Windows process injection PoC
- Mapping injection steps to EDR telemetry and detection rules
- Testing defensive controls around remote memory allocation and remote thread creation
- Training material for understanding Windows injection tradecraft

Keywords:
process injection, Windows internals, OpenProcess, VirtualAllocEx, WriteProcessMemory, VirtualProtectEx, CreateRemoteThread, NtCreateThreadEx, remote thread, code execution, memory permissions, RWX, shellcode, payload staging, handle rights, EDR telemetry, detection engineering, userland injection